<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="164" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,310,1144,1170]" box="[189,310,1144,1170]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1144,1170]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="27" pageNumber="164" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1144,1170]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,1399,1190,1432]" box="[234,306,1190,1216]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,306,1190,1216]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Adult</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,1399,1190,1432]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">
Head with oval frons, which is almost completely covered by median ocellus. Clypeus pear-shaped, in profile hidden by genae and not visible. Propleurites with episternum subequal to or smaller than epimeron. Metacoxa with large, pointed, horn-shaped meracanthus; metatibia with large genual spine, bearing 4–5 irregularly spaced, sclerotised, apical spurs; metabasitarsus with 2 spurs. Forewing rhomboidal; costal break and pterostigma developed; cell cu1 large; anal break close to apex of vein Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[223,241,1418,1432]" fontSize="6" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">1b</subScript>
. Male proctiger one-segmented.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,1399,1464,1631]" box="[234,507,1464,1490]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,507,1464,1490]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Fifth instar immature</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,1399,1464,1631]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Body broadly oval, lacking capitate setae. Antenna with 4 rhinaria. Meso and metathoracic sclerites small. Forewing pad lacking humeral lobes. Margin of hindwing pad usually with one sectaseta. Legs lacking capitate setae; tarsal arolium fan-shaped with unguitractor and pedicel. Caudal plate developed, semi-circular; margin with up to 3+3 sectasetae.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="166" pageId="27" pageNumber="164" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,334,1669,1695]" box="[189,334,1669,1695]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,1669,1695]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="27" pageNumber="164" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,1669,1695]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[188,1400,1715,2025]" box="[234,306,1715,1741]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,306,1715,1741]" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Adult</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[188,1400,1715,2025]" lastBlockId="28.[186,1400,265,608]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="165" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">
Head, in profile, weakly to strongly inclined at 30–90° from longitudinal body axis (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[188,231,1925,1951]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 8. Platycoryphinae subfam. nov.A–B. Allophorina sp.C–D. Limbopsylla nata Brown &amp; Hodkinson, 1988. E–F. Padaukia macrolobii Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz, 2018. G–H. Platycorypha nigrivirga Burckhardt, 1987. A, C, E, G. Habitus, in profile view. B, D, F, H. Head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4594349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4594349/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Fig. 8A, C, E, G</figureCitation>
). Vertex subrectangular to transversely subtrapezoidal (
<figureCitation box="[896,1110,1785,1812]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[188,231,1925,1951]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 8. Platycoryphinae subfam. nov.A–B. Allophorina sp.C–D. Limbopsylla nata Brown &amp; Hodkinson, 1988. E–F. Padaukia macrolobii Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz, 2018. G–H. Platycorypha nigrivirga Burckhardt, 1987. A, C, E, G. Habitus, in profile view. B, D, F, H. Head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4594349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4594349/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Fig. 8B, D, F, H</figureCitation>
); separated from genae sometimes by transverse or oblique suture, sometimes passing smoothly into genae; genae smoothly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[300,427,1855,1882]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[188,231,1925,1951]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 8. Platycoryphinae subfam. nov.A–B. Allophorina sp.C–D. Limbopsylla nata Brown &amp; Hodkinson, 1988. E–F. Padaukia macrolobii Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz, 2018. G–H. Platycorypha nigrivirga Burckhardt, 1987. A, C, E, G. Habitus, in profile view. B, D, F, H. Head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4594349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4594349/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Fig. 8D, H</figureCitation>
) or forming short (
<figureCitation box="[648,734,1855,1882]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="25.[189,232,1839,1865]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,265,1772]" captionTargetId="figure-55@25.[189,1399,265,1772]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Fig. 7. Katacephalinae subfam. nov. A, G. Katacephala longiramis (Burckhardt, 1987). B. Katacephala tenuipennis Tuthill, 1944. C, I. Lautereropsis sp. D, J. Notophorina brevicornis Burckhardt, 1987. E, K. Notophorina sp. F, L. Tuthillia sp. H. Katacephala sp. A–F. Habitus, in profile view. G–L. Head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4594346" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4594346/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Fig. 7F</figureCitation>
) or long conical processes (
<figureCitation box="[1057,1148,1855,1881]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[188,231,1925,1951]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 8. Platycoryphinae subfam. nov.A–B. Allophorina sp.C–D. Limbopsylla nata Brown &amp; Hodkinson, 1988. E–F. Padaukia macrolobii Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz, 2018. G–H. Platycorypha nigrivirga Burckhardt, 1987. A, C, E, G. Habitus, in profile view. B, D, F, H. Head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4594349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4594349/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
); coronal suture fully developed or completely reduced; frons oval, almost completely covered by median ocellus; anteorbital tubercle sometimes developed (
<figureCitation box="[560,655,1927,1953]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[188,231,1925,1951]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 8. Platycoryphinae subfam. nov.A–B. Allophorina sp.C–D. Limbopsylla nata Brown &amp; Hodkinson, 1988. E–F. Padaukia macrolobii Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz, 2018. G–H. Platycorypha nigrivirga Burckhardt, 1987. A, C, E, G. Habitus, in profile view. B, D, F, H. Head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4594349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4594349/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="164">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
: arrow). Antenna 10-segmented, filiform, ranging from slightly longer than head width to distinctly longer than forewing, segment 3 shorter or longer than segments 7 or 8. Clypeus pear-shaped, in profile hidden by genae and not visible. Rostrum usually short, only tip exceeding procoxae, sometimes longer (in some 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tuthill" authorityYear="1945" box="[820,978,265,291]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Platycorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[820,978,265,291]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="165">Platycorypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.). Thorax weakly (
<figureCitation box="[1262,1357,265,291]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="25.[189,232,1839,1865]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,265,1772]" captionTargetId="figure-55@25.[189,1399,265,1772]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Fig. 7. Katacephalinae subfam. nov. A, G. Katacephala longiramis (Burckhardt, 1987). B. Katacephala tenuipennis Tuthill, 1944. C, I. Lautereropsis sp. D, J. Notophorina brevicornis Burckhardt, 1987. E, K. Notophorina sp. F, L. Tuthillia sp. H. Katacephala sp. A–F. Habitus, in profile view. G–L. Head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4594346" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4594346/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="165">Fig. 7G</figureCitation>
) to strongly (
<figureCitation box="[303,396,300,326]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[188,231,1925,1951]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-197@28.[189,1399,659,1883]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 8. Platycoryphinae subfam. nov.A–B. Allophorina sp.C–D. Limbopsylla nata Brown &amp; Hodkinson, 1988. E–F. Padaukia macrolobii Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz, 2018. G–H. Platycorypha nigrivirga Burckhardt, 1987. A, C, E, G. Habitus, in profile view. B, D, F, H. Head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4594349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4594349/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="165">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
) arched dorsally, about as wide as head; pronotum weakly or very strongly inclined from longitudinal body axis; propleurites narrow to broad, with episternum subequal to or smaller than epimeron. Legs moderately long, tibiae often shorter than femora, sometimes subequal or longer; basitarsi not much longer than broad; metacoxa with large, pointed, horn-shaped meracanthus; metatibia with large genual spine, bearing 4–5 irregularly spaced, sclerotised, apical spurs; metabasitarsus with 2 spurs. Forewing rhomboidal, broadest in apical third or in the middle, narrowly rounded or angular apically; membrane semitransparent, covered in surface spinules; costal break and pterostigma developed; vein C+Sc weakly or strongly widened; vein R longer than M+Cu; cell cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[999,1008,565,579]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="165">1</subScript>
large; caudal break close to apex of vein Cu
</paragraph>
<paragraph box="[311,329,601,615]" pageId="28" pageNumber="165">1b</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[186,1400,265,608]" lastBlockId="29.[189,1399,265,362]" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="166" pageId="28" pageNumber="165">. Hindwing slightly shorter than forewing, membranous; costal setae ungrouped or grouped; vein R+M+Cu indistinctly trifurcating or splitting into R and M+Cu. Male proctiger one-segmented; in profile, tubular or with posterior lobe. Male subgenital plate subglobular or elongate. Paramere lamellar or complex. Female terminalia short or moderaly long; proctiger often with dorsal hump.</paragraph>
